## Inspect the prompt

The system + user messages are pure functions on `NamePrompt`. Edit the
module, save, then `r Manillum.Conversations.Conversation.NamePrompt`
in a cell to pick up changes. The fixture below is the same Roman-Empire
conversation that broke the old prompt.

```elixir
alias Manillum.Conversations.Conversation.NamePrompt

sample_messages = [
  %{role: :user, content: "Hello, is this working?"},
  %{role: :assistant, content: "Hello! Yes, this is working perfectly! How can I help?"},
  %{role: :user, content: "Can you give me a timeline history of the Roman empire?"},
  %{role: :assistant, content: "(long markdown timeline elided in this preview…)"}
]

IO.puts("=== SYSTEM ===\n")
IO.puts(NamePrompt.system_message())
IO.puts("\n=== USER ===\n")
IO.puts(NamePrompt.user_message(sample_messages))
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
=== SYSTEM ===

You are a librarian who writes short titles for chat conversations.
Each conversation is between a user and Livy, a history-learning assistant.
Your job is to read the transcript and produce a title naming what the
conversation is about.


=== USER ===

Below are example conversations and their titles, then a new conversation you should title.

<examples>
  <example>
    <conversation>
      <user>Why did the Bronze Age collapse?</user>
      <assistant>Most historians treat it as a systems collapse — between roughly 1200 and 1150 BCE every major palace economy in the eastern Mediterranean fell within fifty years. Drought, severed trade, internal rebellion, and the Sea Peoples all contributed.</assistant>
    </conversation>
    <title>Bronze Age systems collapse</title>
  </example>
  <example>
    <conversation>
      <user>Tell me about the printing press.</user>
      <assistant>Gutenberg's movable-type press around 1440 dropped the cost of books by an order of magnitude over a generation, accelerating literacy, the Reformation, and the scientific revolution.</assistant>
      <user>Was it actually invented in Europe first?</user>
      <assistant>No — Bi Sheng built movable clay type in Song-dynasty China around 1040, four centuries earlier. Gutenberg's innovation was the metal alloy and the press itself, suited to alphabetic scripts.</assistant>
    </conversation>
    <title>Origins of the printing press</title>
  </example>
  <example>
    <conversation>
      <user>What was the spice trade?</user>
      <assistant>The long-distance trade in pepper, cloves, nutmeg, and cinnamon between the Indian Ocean and Europe, dominated by Venice and Arab middlemen until the late 15th century.</assistant>
      <user>How did Portugal break the Venetian monopoly?</user>
      <assistant>Vasco da Gama's 1498 voyage round the Cape of Good Hope opened a sea route to India that bypassed the Mediterranean intermediaries, collapsing Venetian margins within a generation.</assistant>
    </conversation>
    <title>Spice trade and Portuguese expansion</title>
  </example>
</examples>

<conversation>
  <user>Hello, is this working?</user>
  <assistant>Hello! Yes, this is working perfectly! How can I help?</assistant>
  <user>Can you give me a timeline history of the Roman empire?</user>
  <assistant>(long markdown timeline elided in this preview…)</assistant>
</conversation>

Title the conversation above. Format requirements:
- 3 to 8 words.
- Plain text on a single line — no markdown, no quotation marks, no trailing punctuation.
- Sentence case: capitalize the first word and proper nouns. Do not Title-Case every word.
- Describe the subject of the conversation, not the user's intent. Prefer noun phrases like "Bronze Age systems collapse" over "Discussion of the Bronze Age".

Output the title inside <title>…</title> tags. Output nothing else.

```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
:ok
```

## Fixtures

Five conversation shapes, hand-picked to stress different failure modes
of the previous prompt:

* **`:roman_empire`** — the actual broken case from the dev DB. Long,
  bullet-heavy assistant messages. The old prompt drifted into continuing
  the bullet list instead of producing a title.
* **`:bronze_age`** — single clean exchange on a focused topic. The
  baseline "this should obviously work" case.
* **`:greeting_only`** — only a hello and a reply. The conversation has
  no real subject; we want to see what the model does with a stub.
  (In production, `needs_title` won't fire on this — only one message —
  but it's a useful failure-mode probe.)
* **`:topic_drift`** — user asks about A, then pivots to B. The title
  should capture the dominant subject without making up a connection
  that isn't in the text.
* **`:disambiguating`** — a conversation about a specific person where
  several people share the name. The title should pick the right
  qualifier rather than a generic noun phrase.

```elixir
fixtures = %{
  roman_empire: [
    %{role: :user, content: "Hello, is this working? "},
    %{role: :assistant, content: "Hello! Yes, this is working perfectly! I'm here and ready to help you. How can I assist you today?"},
    %{role: :user, content: "Can you give me a timeline history of the roman empire? "},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    # Timeline History of the Roman Empire

    Here's a comprehensive timeline of the Roman Empire:

    ## **Roman Kingdom (753-509 BCE)**
    - **753 BCE** - Traditional founding of Rome by Romulus
    - **509 BCE** - Overthrow of the last king, Tarquin the Proud; Republic established

    ## **Roman Republic (509-27 BCE)**
    - **509-264 BCE** - Expansion throughout Italy
    - **264-241 BCE** - First Punic War (vs. Carthage)
    - **218-201 BCE** - Second Punic War; Hannibal crosses the Alps
    - **149-146 BCE** - Third Punic War; Carthage destroyed
    - **133-121 BCE** - Gracchi brothers' reforms
    - **73-71 BCE** - Spartacus slave revolt
    - **60 BCE** - First Triumvirate (Caesar, Pompey, Crassus)
    - **49 BCE** - Caesar crosses the Rubicon; Civil War begins
    - **44 BCE** - Assassination of Julius Caesar
    - **43 BCE** - Second Triumvirate (Octavian, Mark Antony, Lepidus)
    - **31 BCE** - Battle of Actium; Octavian defeats Antony and Cleopatra

    ## **Roman Empire - Principate (27 BCE - 284 CE)**

    ### **Julio-Claudian Dynasty (27 BCE - 68 CE)**
    - **27 BCE** - Octavian becomes Augustus; Empire begins
    - **14 CE** - Death of Augustus; Tiberius becomes emperor
    - **37-41 CE** - Reign of Caligula
    - **41-54 CE** - Reign of Claudius; conquest of Britain begins (43 CE)
    - **54-68 CE** - Reign of Nero; Great Fire of Rome (64 CE)

    ### **Flavian Dynasty (69-96 CE)**
    - **69-79 CE** - Vespasian; construction of Colosseum begins
    - **79 CE** - Eruption of Mount Vesuvius destroys Pompeii
    - **79-81 CE** - Titus; Colosseum completed
    - **81-96 CE** - Domitian

    ### **Nerva-Antonine Dynasty (96-192 CE) - "Five Good Emperors"**
    - **96-98 CE** - Nerva
    - **98-117 CE** - Trajan; Empire reaches greatest extent (117 CE)
    - **117-138 CE** - Hadrian; Hadrian's Wall built in Britain
    - **138-161 CE** - Antoninus Pius
    - **161-180 CE** - Marcus Aurelius (philosopher-emperor)
    - **180-192 CE** - Commodus

    ## **Fall of the Western Roman Empire**
    - **410 CE** - Visigoths sack Rome
    - **455 CE** - Vandals sack Rome
    - **476 CE** - Romulus Augustulus deposed; Western Empire ends
    """},
    %{role: :user, content: "Where does cicero fall on this timeline? "},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Great question! **Cicero (Marcus Tullius Cicero)** falls during the **late Roman Republic** period.

    ## **Cicero's Timeline (106-43 BCE)**

    - **106 BCE** - Born in Arpinum, Italy
    - **63 BCE** - Served as Consul; exposed the Catiline Conspiracy
    - **58-57 BCE** - Exiled briefly for executing conspirators without trial
    - **51-50 BCE** - Served as governor of Cilicia
    - **49 BCE** - Caesar crosses the Rubicon; Cicero initially supports Pompey
    - **44 BCE** - Julius Caesar assassinated; Cicero supports the conspirators
    - **44-43 BCE** - Delivers his famous "Philippics" against Mark Antony
    - **43 BCE** - Killed on December 7 during the proscriptions of the Second Triumvirate

    He was Rome's greatest orator, a philosopher, lawyer, and statesman who tried to preserve the Republic.
    """}
  ],
  bronze_age: [
    %{role: :user, content: "Why did the Bronze Age collapse?"},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Most historians treat it as a systems collapse. Between roughly 1200 and 1150 BCE,
    nearly every major palace economy in the eastern Mediterranean fell within fifty
    years — Mycenaean Greece, the Hittite Empire, Ugarit, and Cyprus all show
    destruction layers in roughly that window.

    The Sea Peoples are part of the story but not the whole story. Eric Cline's
    framing — that simultaneous stresses (drought, earthquake swarms, internal
    rebellion, severed trade) overwhelmed a fragile interconnected system — is now
    the dominant view. Drought has the strongest material evidence: pollen cores
    from the Sea of Galilee and Cyprus, published by Kaniewski et al. in 2013, show
    a roughly three-hundred-year arid phase beginning around 1200 BC.
    """}
  ],
  greeting_only: [
    %{role: :user, content: "Hello, is this working?"},
    %{role: :assistant, content: "Hello! Yes, this is working perfectly! How can I help?"}
  ],
  topic_drift: [
    %{role: :user, content: "Tell me about the Library of Alexandria."},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Founded around 280 BCE under Ptolemy II, the Library of Alexandria was the
    most ambitious accumulation of written knowledge in the ancient world —
    estimates put its scroll count at 400,000 to 700,000 at its peak. It declined
    over centuries through fire, neglect, and political instability rather than
    a single dramatic event.
    """},
    %{role: :user, content: "What about the Library at Pergamon? Was it a rival?"},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Yes — Pergamon's Attalid kings deliberately built a competing library in the
    2nd century BCE, supposedly large enough that Egypt embargoed papyrus exports
    to slow them down. Pergamon's response was to refine parchment (treated animal
    skin) into a viable writing surface, which is where we get the word "parchment"
    (from "Pergamenum"). Mark Antony reportedly later transferred the Pergamon
    library's holdings to Cleopatra as a gift, though that account is contested.
    """},
    %{role: :user, content: "Was parchment actually a Pergamon invention?"},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Not strictly — treated animal skin had been used as a writing surface for
    centuries before Pergamon. What Pergamon refined was the manufacturing process
    that produced consistent, double-sided, thinner parchment suitable for codex-
    style books. The "invention" attribution is more about scaling and quality
    than first-use.
    """}
  ],
  disambiguating: [
    %{role: :user, content: "Tell me about Charles the Bald."},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Charles II "the Bald" (823–877) was the youngest son of Louis the Pious and
    grandson of Charlemagne. After the 843 Treaty of Verdun divided the Carolingian
    Empire among Louis's sons, Charles received West Francia — roughly the territory
    that would become medieval France. He spent most of his reign defending against
    Viking raids and consolidating control over a fractious nobility, and was
    crowned Holy Roman Emperor in 875, two years before his death.
    """},
    %{role: :user, content: "How did his reign compare to his brother Louis the German's?"},
    %{role: :assistant, content: """
    Louis the German (806–876) ruled East Francia — the German-speaking territories.
    His reign was generally more stable than Charles the Bald's: he faced fewer
    Viking incursions (East Francia was less coastal), his nobility was less
    fragmented, and he reigned for longer over a more cohesive realm. Charles
    inherited the harder problem — defending a long Atlantic and Channel coast
    while managing a magnate class that frequently rebelled — and his ad hoc
    grants of land and title to nobles in exchange for military service helped
    seed the feudal arrangements that defined French governance for the next
    five centuries.
    """}
  ]
}

Map.keys(fixtures)
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
[:roman_empire, :bronze_age, :greeting_only, :topic_drift, :disambiguating]
```

## Run all fixtures through the new prompt

This calls `ReqLLM.generate_text/2` with the model `anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-5`
and `max_tokens: NamePrompt.max_tokens()` (40, by design — see the moduledoc
on `NamePrompt` for why). For each fixture the cell prints:

* the parsed title (or the parser's error reason)
* the title's character length
* the raw text the model returned (so you can compare against the
  parser's interpretation)

If a fixture errored, the `ERROR:` line carries the parser's reason
(`:title_too_long`, `:title_contains_markdown`, `:empty_title`) or a
`ReqLLM error: …` for transport / auth failures.

```elixir
run_fixture = fn name, messages ->
  prompt = NamePrompt.build(messages)

  case ReqLLM.generate_text("anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-5", prompt,
         max_tokens: NamePrompt.max_tokens()
       ) do
    {:ok, response} ->
      raw = ReqLLM.Response.text(response)

      case NamePrompt.parse_response(raw) do
        {:ok, title} ->
          %{fixture: name, raw: raw, title: title, len: String.length(title), error: nil}

        {:error, reason} ->
          %{fixture: name, raw: raw, title: nil, len: nil, error: inspect(reason)}
      end

    {:error, error} ->
      %{
        fixture: name,
        raw: nil,
        title: nil,
        len: nil,
        error: "ReqLLM error: #{inspect(error)}"
      }
  end
end

print_result = fn r ->
  IO.puts("─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────")
  IO.puts("fixture:  #{inspect(r.fixture)}")

  if r.error do
    IO.puts("ERROR:    #{r.error}")
  else
    IO.puts("title:    #{r.title}")
    IO.puts("length:   #{r.len} chars")
  end

  if r.raw, do: IO.puts("raw:      #{inspect(r.raw)}")
end

results =
  fixtures
  |> Enum.map(fn {name, messages} -> run_fixture.(name, messages) end)

Enum.each(results, print_result)

IO.puts("─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────")
IO.puts("ran #{length(results)} fixtures · #{Enum.count(results, & &1.error)} errored")
```

## Iterate on a single fixture

Sometimes you want to focus on one conversation while you tune the prompt.
Edit the fixture key, re-evaluate the cell, and only that one runs.

```elixir
focus_fixture = :roman_empire

focus_messages = fixtures[focus_fixture]
focus_prompt = NamePrompt.build(focus_messages)

case ReqLLM.generate_text("anthropic:claude-sonnet-4-5", focus_prompt,
       max_tokens: NamePrompt.max_tokens()
     ) do
  {:ok, response} ->
    raw = ReqLLM.Response.text(response)

    %{
      fixture: focus_fixture,
      raw: raw,
      parsed: NamePrompt.parse_response(raw)
    }

  {:error, error} ->
    %{fixture: focus_fixture, error: error}
end
```

## Sign-off checklist

Before wiring `NamePrompt` into `Manillum.Conversations.Conversation.Changes.GenerateName`
in production, the run-all cell above should:

* [ ] **`:roman_empire`** — produce a 3–8 word title; no markdown; no
  ```
  `Roman Empire` style Title-Case-Of-Every-Word; ideally something
  like `Roman Empire timeline overview` or `Roman Empire and Cicero`
  that captures both the timeline ask and the Cicero follow-up.
  ```
* [ ] **`:bronze_age`** — clean noun phrase, e.g. `Bronze Age systems collapse`.
* [ ] **`:greeting_only`** — the model should produce *something* (the
  ```
  `:title_too_long` and markdown checks will catch the worst cases),
  but content quality on a stub is intrinsically limited. Acceptable
  outputs include `Greeting and setup test`, `Connection check`, etc.
  The point of this fixture isn't a great title — it's that we don't
  crash or produce 300 chars of bullet points.
  ```
* [ ] **`:topic_drift`** — captures the dominant thread (Library of
  ```
  Alexandria + Pergamon rivalry) without making up a synthesis the
  conversation didn't reach.
  ```
* [ ] **`:disambiguating`** — uses the qualifier "Charles the Bald" or
  ```
  "Carolingian succession", not just `Charles` or `medieval kings`.
  ```
* [ ] No fixture errors with `:title_too_long` or `:title_contains_markdown`.

When all five pass, wire `NamePrompt` into the production change module
in a follow-up PR.
